9.How is Cell Padding different from Cell Spacing? With Example.\par
\b0 -Cell padding and cell spacing are both used to add space around table cells in HTML, but they are used in different ways.\par
Cell padding is used to add space within a cell. It specifies the amount of space between the cell content and the cell border. Here's an example:\par
<table>\par
  <tr>\par
    <td style="padding: 10px;">Cell 1</td>\par
    <td style="padding: 10px;">Cell 2</td>\par
  </tr>\par
</table>\par
In this example, the 'padding' style is used to add 10 pixels of space within each cell.\par
Cell spacing, on the other hand, is used to add space between cells. It specifies the amount of space between adjacent cells in a table. Here's an example:\par
<table style="border-spacing: 10px;">\par
  <tr>\par
    <td>Cell 1</td>\par
    <td>Cell 2</td>\par
  </tr>\par
  <tr>\par
    <td>Cell 3</td>\par
    <td>Cell 4</td>\par
  </tr>\par
</table>\par
In this example, the 'border-spacing' style is used to add 10 pixels of space between adjacent cells.\par
So, the key difference between cell padding and cell spacing is that cell padding adds space within cells, while cell spacing adds space between cells.\par
\b\lang9\par
10.How can we club two or more rows or columns into a single row or column in an HTML table? With Example.\par
-\b0 In HTML, you can merge two or more rows or columns into a single row or column using the 'rowspan' and 'colspan' attributes on the appropriate table cells.\par
To merge two or more columns into a single column, use the 'colspan' attribute on the first cell of the group, and set its value to the number of columns to be merged. Here's an example:\par
<table>\par
  <tr>\par
    <td>Cell 1</td>\par
    <td colspan="2">Cell 2 & 3</td>\par
    <td>Cell 4</td>\par
  </tr>\par
</table>\par
In this example, the second cell spans two columns, effectively merging Cell 2 and Cell 3 into a single cell.\par
To merge two or more rows into a single row, use the 'rowspan' attribute on the first cell of the group, and set its value to the number of rows to be merged. Here's an example:\par
<table>\par
  <tr>\par
    <td rowspan="2">Cell 1 & 3</td>\par
    <td>Cell 2</td>\par
  </tr>\par
  <tr>\par
    <td>Cell 4</td>\par
  </tr>\par
</table>\par
In this example, the first cell spans two rows, effectively merging Cell 1 and Cell 3 into a single cell.\par
So, by using 'rowspan' and 'colspan' attributes, you can easily merge two or more rows or columns into a single row or column in an HTML table.\par
