11.What is the difference between a block-level element and an inline element?\par
\b0 -In HTML, block-level elements and inline elements are used to define the structure and layout of web pages.\par
Block-level elements are used to create larger structures on a web page, such as paragraphs, headings, and lists. They take up the full width of their parent container and create a new line after the element. Here's an example:\par
<p>This is a block-level element.</p>\par
In this example, the 'p' element is a block-level element that creates a new line after the element, and takes up the full width of its parent container.\par
Inline elements, on the other hand, are used to create smaller structures on a web page, such as links, emphasized text, and images. They do not create a new line after the element, and only take up as much width as necessary. Here's an example:\par
<a href="#">This is an inline element.</a>\par
In this example, the 'a' element is an inline element that does not create a new line after the element, and only takes up as much width as necessary.\par
So, the key difference between block-level elements and inline elements is that block-level elements create larger structures and take up the full width of their parent container, while inline elements create smaller structures and only take up as much width as necessary.\par
\b\par
