15. How to insert a picture into a background image of a web page? With Example.\par
\b0 -In HTML, you can add a background image to a web page using the 'background-image' style property. Here's an example of how to add a background image to a web page:\par
\par
body \{\par
  background-image: url("background-image.jpg");\par
\}\par
In this example, the 'background-image' style property is used to add the image file "background-image.jpg" as the background image for the 'body' element. The 'url' function is used to specify the URL of the image file.\par
To insert an image into the background image, you can use the 'background' style property with the 'url' function to specify the background image, and then use the 'content' property to insert the image. Here's an example:\par
body \{\par
  background: url("background-image.jpg") no-repeat center center fixed;\par
  background-size: cover;\par
\}\par
#image \{\par
  position: absolute;\par
  top: 50%;\par
  left: 50%;\par
  transform: translate(-50%, -50%);\par
  content: url("image.jpg");\par
\}\par
In this example, the 'background' style property is used to add the image file "background-image.jpg" as the background image for the 'body' element. The 'no-repeat' value is used to prevent the background image from repeating, and the 'center center fixed' values are used to center the background image and prevent it from scrolling. The 'background-size' property is used to set the size of the background image to cover the entire screen.\par
The '#image' selector is used to select the element that will contain the inserted image. The 'position' property is used to position the element in the center of the screen, and the 'transform' property is used to center the element horizontally and vertically. The 'content' property is used to insert the image file "image.jpg" into the element.\par
So, by using the 'background' style property with the 'url' function and the 'content' property, you can easily insert an image into the background image of a web page.\par
