18. What is SVG?\par
\b0 -SVG stands for Scalable Vector Graphics, which is a type of image format that uses vector graphics to create images that can be scaled up or down without losing quality. Unlike raster graphics, which are made up of pixels, vector graphics are made up of mathematical equations that describe the shape and position of each element in the image. This makes SVG images ideal for use on the web, where they can be resized to fit different screen sizes and resolutions.\par
\b\par
19. What is difference between HTML and XHTML?\b0\par
-HTML and XHTML are both markup languages used to create web pages, but there are some key differences between them:\par
- Syntax: HTML uses a relatively loose syntax, allowing for some errors and inconsistencies, while XHTML has a stricter syntax that requires all elements to be properly nested and closed.\par
- Tag names: HTML allows for tag names to be written in uppercase or lowercase, while XHTML requires all tag names to be written in lowercase.\par
- Attribute values: HTML allows for attribute values to be unquoted or wrapped in single quotes, while XHTML requires all attribute values to be wrapped in double quotes.\par
- Document structure: HTML allows for certain elements to be omitted or written in a simplified form, while XHTML requires a more complete and consistent document structure.\par
Overall, XHTML is considered to be a more rigorous and standardized version of HTML, but it can also be more difficult to write and maintain due to its stricter syntax and requirements.\par
\b\par
20. What are logical and physical tags in HTML?\par
\b0 -In HTML, logical tags are used to describe the meaning or purpose of a section of content, while physical tags are used to describe the appearance or presentation of the content. \par
Logical tags include elements such as <header>, <nav>, <main>, <section>, <article>, and <footer>, which are used to structure and organize the content of a web page in a semantic way. These tags provide information about the meaning and purpose of the content, which can be useful for search engines, screen readers, and other tools that rely on structured data.\par
Physical tags, on the other hand, include elements such as <b>, <i>, <u>, <font>, and <br>, which are used to apply formatting and styling to the content of a web page. These tags describe the appearance of the content, rather than its meaning, and can be used to change the font, color, size, and other visual properties of the text.\par
While physical tags can be useful for creating a specific visual style or layout, they should be used sparingly and in conjunction with logical tags to ensure that the content remains accessible and meaningful to all users, regardless of their device or abilities.\par
